<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-04-0592 </DOCNO><TEXT>Reviews production increase and introduction of computer technology inthe GDR brown coal industry. Between 1970 and 1980 automation focusedon operation of overburden conveyor bridges, surface mine drainage systemsand railway mine haulage. Since 1980, decentralized office computersfor a wide range of tasks have been introduced. Their number will increasein the brown coal industry to 1,000 units by 1990. At the same time,the number of employees applying computer technology will increase to8,000, while the overall work force in the industry is planned to bereduced by 2,500 by 1990. It is estimated that cost of automation willamount to 1 to 3% of the total coal industry investment and will resultin 5 to 10% higher coal production. General fields of possibilities forcomputer application in the GDR brown coal industry are listed. 3 refs.</TEXT></DOC>